Sure! Here’s a playful and fun little Java code snippet that defines a method to check if a given number is a "merry prime". A "merry prime" is just a fun term for a prime number that's also a happy number. A happy number is a number which eventually reaches 1 when replaced by the sum of the square of each digit.

```java
public class MerryPrimeChecker {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Is 7 a merry prime? " + isMerryPrime(7));
        System.out.println("Is 13 a merry prime? " + isMerryPrime(13));
    }

    public static boolean isPrime(int number) {
        if (number <= 1) return false;
        for (int i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(number); i++) {
            if (number % i == 0) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

    public static boolean isHappy(int number) {
        int slow = number, fast = number;
        do {
            slow = sumOfSquares(slow);
            fast = sumOfSquares(sumOfSquares(fast));
        } while (slow != fast);
        return slow == 1;
    }

    private static int sumOfSquares(int n) {
        int sum = 0;
        while (n > 0) {
            int digit = n % 10;
            sum += digit * digit;
            n /= 10;
        }
        return sum;
    }

    public static boolean isMerryPrime(int number) {
        return isPrime(number) && isHappy(number);
    }
}
```

In this snippet:
- `isPrime(int number)` checks if a number is prime.
- `isHappy(int number)` checks if a number is happy.
- `sumOfSquares(int n)` calculates the sum of the squares of the digits of a number.
- `isMerryPrime(int number)` combines the checks for being both a prime and a happy number.

Feel free to test it out with different numbers and see if they're merry primes! 🎉
